aa(lp213
VFinally,
p214
aVlet me tell you one last story.
p215
aVOn July 16, 1945,
p216
aVon the White Sands of New Mexico,
p217
aVan atomic bomb was detonated for the first time.
p218
aVAs a result of this explosion,
p219
aVa cloud of radioactive particles disseminated all over the earth,
p220
aVmarking the beginning of the Anthropocene era.
p221
aVSeventy years later, on November 8, 2015,
p222
aVin the same place,
p223
aVanother event occurred.
p224
aVFor the first time in history,
p225
aVwe lifted a person into the air using only the sun,
p226
aVwithout burning any fossil fuels.
p227
aVAs the sun rose up above the horizon,
p228
aVwe rose up, too,
p229
aVsilently,
p230
aVslowly,
p231
aVwith no explosions.
p232
aVWe felt as if gravity had been inverted;
p233
aVit wasn't pulling us toward the center of the earth,
p234
aVbut toward the universe.
p235
aVIf Neil Armstrong said, when he walked on the moon,
p236
aV"That's one small step for man,
p237
aVone giant leap for mankind,"
p238
aVperhaps what we ought to ask ourselves is:
p239
aVWhat steps do we need to take today?
